\begin{abstract}
Link prediction is a fundamental task in graphs, where the goal is to predict missing links between nodes. Most existing approaches rely on node embeddings learned by graph neural networks and use simple decoders for link prediction, often overlooking global structural information such as the shortest-path distance between nodes. In this work, we propose a distance-augmented link prediction framework that incorporates shortest-path distance into link prediction. We encode distances using sinusoidal embeddings and use them to condition the decoder through adaptive layer normalization, allowing the model to adjust node representations based on structural proximity. Our experiments on the CORA dataset demonstrates that incorporating distance information leads to improved link prediction performance.
\end{abstract}
\vspace{0.5em}
\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Link Prediction, Graph Neural Networks (GNN), GraphSAGE, Distance Encoding, Adaptive Layer Normalization (AdaLN).
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}
Link prediction is a fundamental problem in graph learning with applications in social networks, citation networks, recommendation systems, and biological networks. The task involves predicting if an edge exists between two nodes based on the observed structure of the graph and node features. With the success of graph neural networks (GNNs) \cite{kipf2016variational}, link prediction is approached using an encoder–decoder framework, where the encoder generates node embeddings and the decoder estimates the likelihood of a link between node pairs.
\vspace{0.5em}

While significant effort has been devoted to designing more expressive encoders, the decoder in many existing approaches remains relatively simple, often relying on dot products or shallow multilayer perceptrons \cite{kipf2016variational, wang2021benchmark}. As a result, these methods primarily depend on node embeddings and may fail to fully utilize important structural signals present in the graph.
\vspace{0.5em}

One such signal is the shortest-path distance between nodes. Nodes that are closer in the graph are usually more likely to be connected than those that are far apart. However, this information is not incorporated in most standard link prediction models, as message passing in GNNs primarily captures local neighborhood information.
\vspace{0.5em}

In this paper, we propose a distance-augmented link prediction framework that  incorporates shortest-path distance into the decoding process. We first compute node embeddings using a GraphSAGE encoder \cite{hamilton2017graphsage}. We then encode the shortest-path distance between node pairs using sinusoidal frequency embeddings, which provide a smooth and expressive representation of distance. These embeddings are used to condition a decoder through AdaLN-Zero \cite{peebles2023dit}, enabling the model to modulate node representations based on structural distance before predicting links.

\vspace{0.5em}

Our approach highlights the importance of combining node embeddings with global structural information for link prediction. We show that incorporating distance information into the decoder leads to more expressive models and improved predictive performance.

\section{Related Work}

Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) have become the dominant approach for link prediction in graph-structured data \cite{zhang2018seal,wang2021benchmark}. These models learn node representations by aggregating information from local neighborhoods \cite{kipf2017gcn}. One widely used method is GraphSAGE, which learns node embeddings by sampling and aggregating features from neighboring nodes \cite{hamilton2017graphsage}. 

\vspace{0.5em}

Many link prediction methods rely on relatively simple decoders \cite{kipf2016variational,wang2021benchmark}. As a result, the performance of these models often depends primarily on the quality of node embeddings, while the decoder plays a limited role in modeling structural relationships between node pairs.

\subsection{Link Prediction Methods}

Traditional link prediction methods include heuristic approaches such as Common Neighbors, Adamic--Adar, and Preferential Attachment, which rely on hand-crafted structural features \cite{liben2007linkprediction}. More recent learning-based methods use node embeddings generated by GNNs and predict links using similarity measures such as dot product, cosine similarity, or learned multilayer perceptrons \cite{kipf2016variational,wang2021benchmark}.

\vspace{0.5em}

While these methods are effective, they typically rely only on node embeddings and do not explicitly incorporate global structural information such as shortest-path distance. As a result, they may fail to capture important structural patterns that influence link formation.


\subsection{Adaptive Normalization and Feature Modulation}

Adaptive Layer Normalization-Zero (AdaLN-Zero) was first introduced in the "Scalable Diffusion Models with Transformers" \cite{peebles2023dit} paper as a means to incorporate information from heterogeneous embeddings (timestep and class embeddings). Precursors of AdaLN-Zero have also been used in deep learning to combine multimodal contextual information \cite{perez2018film}. In these methods, embeddings containing external context are used to generate shift and scale parameters that modulate feature representations. This allows the model to adapt its behavior based on contextual information.

\vspace{0.5em}

In this work, we apply a variant of AdaLN-Zero in the context of link prediction, where shortest-path distance is used as a conditioning signal to modulate node embeddings before decoding. This allows the decoder to adapt its predictions based on the structural relationship between nodes.

