\section{Conclusion}

In this work, we studied the problem of link prediction in graphs and proposed a distance-conditioned decoding approach that incorporates shortest-path distance information into the link prediction model. While standard graph neural networks capture local neighborhood information through message passing, they do not explicitly model global structural relationships between nodes. To address this limitation, we introduced a decoder that conditions node representations on shortest-path distance using a technique inspired by AdaLN-Zero \cite{peebles2023dit}.

\vspace{0.5em}

We explored multiple ways of incorporating distance information, including raw distance concatenation, distance embeddings, and distance-conditioned adaptive normalization. Our experiments show that incorporating structural distance significantly improves link prediction performance, and conditioning node embeddings using distance through AdaLN-Zero performs better than simple concatenation.

\vspace{0.5em}

These results suggest that global structural signals such as shortest-path distance provide useful information for link prediction that is not fully captured by node embeddings alone. The proposed approach shows that conditioning mechanisms like AdaLN-Zero can be an effective way to integrate structural information into graph-based models.

\vspace{0.5em}

In future work, this approach could be extended by exploring other structural signals such as random walk distances, common neighbor scores, or learned structural encodings. Additionally, more efficient methods for computing or approximating shortest-path distances could improve the scalability of the approach to larger graphs.

\vspace{0.5em}

Overall, this work highlights the importance of combining node embeddings with global structural information for improving link prediction in graphs.





